This document describes the quantitative analysis our paper Revisiting the concept of the âNeolithic Founder Cropsâ in southwest Asia (Arranz-Otaegui & Roe 2022). A research compendium containing the data and R code needed to reproduce the analysis can be accessed at https://github.com/joeroe/SWAsiaNeolithicFounderCrops).

Methods & Materials

Study region and period

Figure 1: The study region

We aimed to collate archaeobotanical data from Southwest Asia (fig.Â 1) from the Neolithic period, c.Â 11,700 â 6500 BP (table 1). To mitigate against an âedge effectâ, we also included samples in the source databases dated to the preceding Late Epipalaeolithic (c.Â 15,000â11,700 BP) and succeeding Chalcolithic (c.Â 6500â5000 BP).

Table 1: Cultural periods used in the analysis
Period Agricultural stage Start (cal BP) End (cal BP
Late Epipal. Foraging 15000 11700
PPNA Pre-domestication cultivation 11700 10700
EPPNB Domestication 10700 10200
MPPNB Domestication 10200 9500
LPPNB/C Agriculture 9500 8500
Pottery Neolithic Agriculture 8500 6500
Chalcolithic Agriculture 6500 5000

Archaeobotanical data

We collated data from three large-scale archaeobotanical databases: ORIGINS (Wallace et al. 2018), and COMPAG (Lucas and Fuller 2018; Fuller et al. 2018), and ADEMNES (Riehl and KÃ¼mmel 2005).

The process of importing, cleaning, and making these databases comparable (see R functions in R/data.R for full details) was fairly involved. In short, we:

  • Standardised site names across databases using the thesaurus compiled at https://github.com/joeroe/swapdata
  • Standardised taxonomic names across databases and applied our additional classifications (described in analysis/data/raw_data/founder_crops.tsv)
  • When sites were in multiple databases, preferred records from the most detailed/recent one (i.e.Â ORIGINS > COMPAG > ADEMNES)
  • ORIGINS is recorded by sample, but COMPAG and ADEMNES by phase, so we aggregated ORIGINS by phase for comparability (and because individual samples are more likely to be ânoisyâ)
  • Calculated phase-level proportions for COMPAG

We filtered this data to include only samples from our region (Southwest Asia) and period (11,700â6500 BP) of interest, with a buffer of Â±2,000 years to reduce âedge effectsâ in our time series analyses.

The resulting collated dataset (analysis/data/derived_data/swasia_neolithic_flora.tsv) includes archaeobotanical assemblages representing 308 distinct phases from 180 sites.

Chronological data

All three databases include rough absolute date ranges (in the vast majority of cases summarised the available radiocarbon dates) for each sample. Using this data, each phase was classified into one of the cultural periods defined above using its mid-point date (table 2).

Table 2: Sites and assemblages per period
Period Sites Assemblages
Late Epipal. 4 6
PPNA 25 29
EPPNB 10 11
MPPNB 22 37
LPPNB/C 32 44
Pottery Neolithic 26 36
Chalcolithic 98 139

For a finer-grained chronology, we also sliced the assemblages into century bins. An assemblage was considered to belong to a bin (e.g.Â 5000â5099 BP) if any part of its absolute date range falls within that bin â this results in the duplication of data across bins, but better reflects the inherent imprecision of radiocarbon dating.

Sample coverage

We are now in a position to inspect the geographical (fig.Â 2) and temporal 3 coverage of the data. Unsurprisingly, the distribution is uneven. Notably, we have few Epipalaeolithic sites, but a very large number of Chalcolithic sites; the regional coverage reflects broader trends in the research history of the region, with a large body of evidence from the Southern Levant, especially for earlier periods, and the rest of the region more patchily covered. Nevertheless, we have a decent baseline number of samples for each time slice in our analysisâthe lowest is 11 assemblages, for the EPPNBâespecially for the key Neolithic periods.

We can also look at the abundance of the founder crops â this time varying P, the proportion of the assemblage accounted for by the founder crops.

Here we exclude some records from the source databases (primarily ADEMNES) which do not actually contain quantitative information in the âproportionâ field, and instead use it to represent presence/absence. We will do the same for following analyses that use abundance measures.
